The `==` operator checks if the two operands are the same object in memory, which is not what you want when comparing strings. Strings are immutable, so they can't change their content after they're created, but they can still be reassigned to a different memory location.

The `.equals()` method, on the other hand, compares the contents of the strings, regardless of their memory location. It's the proper way to compare strings in Java.

In general, you should avoid using `==` to compare strings, as it can lead to unexpected results. For example:
```
String s1 = "Hello";
String s2 = new String("Hello");

// This will print "true", even though s1 and s2 are different objects
System.out.println(s1 == s2);

// This will print "false", because the contents are compared
System.out.println(s1.equals(s2));
```
In summary, use `.equals()` to compare strings in Java, and avoid using `==` for this purpose. The exception is when you specifically want to check if two strings are the same object in memory, which is rare.

